The Solar_Uri class has a number of public properties, all related to the parsed URI processed by Solar_Uri::import().  They are:

||~ Name ||~ Type ||~ Description ||
|| \\schema\\ || string || The schema protocol; e.g.: http, https, ftp, mailto ... ||
|| \\host\\ || string || The host name; e.g.: example.com ||
|| \\user\\ || string || The username for the URI ||
|| \\pass\\ || string || The password for the URI ||
|| \\path\\ || string || The file path portion of the URI, including the page or script name ||
|| \\info\\ || array || A sequential array of path-info elements ||
|| \\query\\ || array || An associative array of query terms ||
|| \\fragment\\ || string || The anchor or page fragment being addressed ||

As an example, the following URI would parse into these properties:

<code>
http://anonymous::guest@example.com/path/to/index.php/foo/bar?baz=dib#anchor
...
schema   => 'http'
host     => 'example.com'
user     => 'anonymous'
pass     => 'guest'

path     => '/path/to/index.php'
info     => array('foo', 'bar')
query    => array('baz' => 'dib')
fragment => 'anchor'
</code>

Although methods exist to let you manipulate the query and info components (c.f. the QueryMethods and InfoMethods pages), you are free to access all these properties directly if you wish.